\b Discussion (Part 1)\b0\par
The probe type significantly influences the measured waveform at the switching node, especially the observed ringing amplitude and duration. Differential probing reduces ground-referencing issues, while passive probes can introduce artifacts through ground lead inductance and probe capacitance. Low-Z probing changes the loading and can alter ringing behavior; it may also increase probe dissipation and limit measurable voltage range. Bandwidth limitations of probe and oscilloscope can distort rise/fall time and overshoot measurements.\par
\par

\b 2.4.2 Measurement Evaluation for Part 2 (gate charge determination)\b0\par
\b Method and assumptions\b0\par
With Rg = 3.3 ohm, the gate current is calculated from the measured gate resistor voltage and gate charge is obtained by integrating the current over the switching transition interval. Measurement errors can be introduced by probe capacitance (\~1 pF), limited CMRR in high-side measurements, and bandwidth/noise limitations.\par
